'I don't just consume coffee. Coffee consumes me.' #tesspresso 
Who are your favourite Coffee Roasters in Australia?

My 'spotlight on the roaster' series brings me to one of Melbourne's most humble, passionate, and kind-hearted humans. Anyone who knows Marwin Shaw will agree, the world is a better place because he exists.

Marwin has been roasting in an unassuming backstreet of Balaclava for a decade now, and 
offers some of the world's most exquisite coffee. He also has a beautiful outlook on life, and I still remember the day he told me that the richest way to live is to be completely engaged with, and dedicated to, what you are doing, in the here and now. I immediately felt my own inner desire to saturate my mind and palate with wholesome goodness... And thus #tesspresso was born.

Thank you, Marwin.

I've got my sights set on roasters this month, as I'm preparing my palate for judging. ****** I must pay respect to a beautiful lady in coffee who taught me the ropes several years ago, in an effort to help me understand what goes on behind the scenes at a roastery... And exactly what goes into creating a roast profile. If you haven't met @roastresscoops yet, then you're missing out. I'm grateful to call her a friend. ****** Find her at her Brunswick digs, 👉 @foundercoffee.

The cafe it resides in has some delicious brews, and eats! Try the Octopus Hash... A #tesspresso favourite!

Whats your most memorable coffee moment? 
Who were you with? **********
I want to share the best coffee moments you all have.

I've long been an advocate of women in coffee, and so many have paved the way for future female coffee professionals. One such human is @baristayan. 
I've watched Yanina grow from her humble beginnings at Ona Coffee a decade ago, when she moved from Argentina. Yanina has gone on to become a National Brewers Champion, and a globally respected barista that has competed on the world stage. She now travels the globe in search of the most delicious green beans, so that us coffee-loving folks can enjoy quality delicious brews with the knowledge that farmers are treated ethically. 
I look forward to catching up with Yanina in May, when some of the most influential coffee professionals in the world converge on Melbourne.

Do you take your pooch out on cafe visits? 🐕

I recently went to a cafe and shared a table with this little angel. I don't have a dog (yet), but I'm thinking of getting one soon ( We already have a name.. Max!) .... And I will be taking Max on weekend cafe visits. 
Let me know which cafes are #petfriendly 😘 🐕

Established almost 5 years ago by husband and wife duo, Dean & Petra Parker, Mr Hoffman sits on the edge of a little shopping strip on one of the main thoroughfares, Hoffmans Road.

Back then, the area was void of a community focused café locals could call their own, and many would travel east for that quintessential Melbourne coffee experience.

Meeting Petra solidified why this café is such a success. Having spent most her career as a teacher, you quickly realise how nurturing this café owner really is, and how her team completely emulates that care she fundamentally possesses. Effortlessly, may I add!... At the core of Mr Hoffman is a commitment to quality without compromise, both in product and experience. This has evolved from years of listening to what locals want, and creating an oasis where many retreat to.

I do believe what attracted me to this café, and everything it stands for, is its communal attitude. The staff, are like close family, customers become friends, and the care factor is at the forefront of every decision made. This is seen right down to the menu, which champions locally sourced and seasonal produce that’s both honest and nourishing, catering for an array of dietary requirements. The recent introduction of Califia Farms Oat Milk, which is used both as an alternative offering for milk coffee drinkers, and in the Bircher Muesli Dish. This dish stays true to its vegan status, sweetened with myrtle syrup and not honey, which marries wonderfully with coconut yoghurt.

Chatting with head barista Marcelo, I discovered that Oat Milk has taken off among coffee drinkers looking for a healthy alternative to dairy milk.  It’s a bonus that it’s such an easy product to use, and Marcelo has been relieved his latte art quality isn’t compromised.

Where am I? 
This concrete heavy, modern take on Melbourne's cafe culture, presents an ideal canvas upon which food shines.

You just need to look at the Nutella Panna Cotta these guys are famed for... Which is up on @melbournehuntress.
"We're constantly reminded to pour our heart into everything we do".

Nelson Box Hill.

Melbourne’s latest café is brought to us by Only Hospitality, who also have MOB Camberwell, Stanley, and Bentwood Fitzroy to name just a few. 
Julien Moussi, Tony Pantone, and Nicky Campbell thought they’d spread their wings further East, and perched themselves across the road from Box Hill Tafe, on Nelson Road.  Julien’s wife Kristy grew up in this bustling eastern suburb, so when the position became available at the base of an apartment complex, they jumped at the opportunity. 
Designed by Zunica, the sleek space is the perfect canvas for food and coffee to shine.

Speaking of food, The Fig & Mascarpone dish with grilled stone-fruit was inspired by a favourite London café Julien frequents while abroad, which demonstrates just how tasty a fresh and simple dish can actually be. The Smashed Kabocha Pumpkin with Feta and Beetroot Hummus also proved to be a delicious cure for that mid-morning ‘hungry hit’, which paired well with the Kenyan espresso roasted by Inglewood. 
Massive congratulations to Julien and the Only Hospitality Group for bringing us another winning venue.

You know what they say about Sunday mornings... #easystreet ⛽☕⛽☕⛽ (And no... I don't get paid to post these moments. My friend Candy has a daughter who makes coffee every morning on this little device. It's adorable. It makes me clucky!!! Yes, I did just say that 🙈). #tesspresso

Many of you will know the prominent pineapple-patterned wallpaper at this Bank Street site. 
Where am I? At the birthplace of Aucuba Coffee, and where Mark Knapp has set his own Benchmark.

He has been roasting some exciting coffee lately.... Watch this space.

#tesspresso

I recently discovered Norwood, a cafe housed in the sustainability driven 'Burwood Brickworks', on Middleborough Road. 
What I love about this site, is that it boasts its own ‘Living Building Challenge (LBC)’, which is regarded as the most advanced measure of sustainability in the built environment. 
Seemingly, in order to achieve LBC accreditation, a building must operate as effectively as a flower – getting all of its energy needs from the sun, using and circulating water, producing no waste or toxicity and looking visually appealing and vibrant. 
I must say, It makes for a great story! 
What else makes this corner spot appealing is the fact they roast their own coffee. A quick chat to the barista soon revealed he was also responsible for roasting the beans that went into making my coffee, so it was a true representation of what he’s hoping to achieve with the Burundi I was offered. A sweet espresso, it had tart acidity, with a creamy mouthfeel, and notes of dark chocolate with cranberry. 
On the food front, the South American Breakfast did fascinate me. What makes for the perfect South American Breakfast? Well, according to these guys; Colombian corn cake with smoked salmon, tomato salsa, whipped avo, fresh cheese, chimichurri, and a fried egg. I can see exactly why. 
The local favourite is no surprise: Hotcakes with lemon curd, raspberry butter cream, and thyme syrup (see @melbournehuntressfor 📷).

Let’s be frank, bread is the most widely consumed food in the world. Humans have been baking it for thousands of years. So how do you stand out from the crowd in Melbourne?  To be Frank, it’s all in the fermentation. That’s what Franco from ‘To be Frank’ focuses on at his new Collingwood bakery. 
He chose to open his latest venue in Collingwood because of the sense of community ingrained (pardon the pun) in this inner-city suburb. 
Being a trained pastry chef/baker, Franco has worked in fine dining restaurants in Buenos Aires, Patagonia, and Uruguay. He moved to Australia in 2012 and worked at Bacash for 5 years, before a stint with friend Jonathan Valdman at a French bakery in Bangkok. Franco fell in love with Jon's style of baking, and decided to bring it to Australia. ‘To Be Frank’ is a reference to baking honest bread. Franco sources all his raw ingredients from producers employing sustainable farming practices, and the style of bread he bakes is different to any other in Melbourne. This is because he produces a long fermentation bread made with minimal yeast. 
What caught my attention? 
Franco’s dedication to sustainable practices, and his commitment to not providing single use takeaway cups. It’s a risk in this coffee obsessed and time poor city, but it’s timely. The reusable coffee cup system seems to be working well so far, and locals are loving the coffee care of Symmetry Coffee Roasters. 
If you enjoy ethically sourced and served coffee, and are curious about how bread is made, then ‘To Be Frank’ is the place for you. 
In a time when people are changing the way they view food, and are reverting back to traditional methods which are better for our health and the planet, ‘To Be Frank’ offers a space to sit and soak up the goodness, whilst encouraging people to be more conscious about where their food comes from and how it’s made. I’m a strong proponent of anyone who wants to be part of a movement that aims to feed their community with real food… and pair it with delicious coffee.

Brighton is famed for its beach boxes, bayside bike trail, and health-conscious residents.

So, it would come as no surprise that a café in the thick of it, caters for bike riders, mindful eaters, and beach go-ers. Superrandom sees Ibrahim Houli at the helm, who knows a thing or two about the café culture. He’s owned several cafes around town, including Wee Jeanie in Yarraville. A move down South sees Ibrahim catering to locals who know what they want, and how they want it. Doors open early here, and a back entrance permits bikes to be walked through into a safe space so riders can enjoy a pit-stop without worry. 
Health is also kept front of mind, which is what motivated Ibrahim’s choice in Oat Milk. The espresso blend at Superrandom has a traditional Italian style; with a rich body and flavours of dark cocoa and roasted hazelnuts that work great with @califiafarms Oat Milk. The two seem to pair well together, not only making life easy for the barista, but is also convenient for the health-conscious consumer wanting a plant-based alternative, not tasting too different from dairy milk.  Several of the mindful-eating local foodies have already made the transition to Oat, indicating Califia is a safe gateway for the shift.

Admittedly, you certainly won’t see me in lycra riding to this New Street café. However, you may see me appreciating a café serving specialty coffee in this prestigious bayside suburb, whilst offering a quality flavour experience for alternative milk drinkers.

I’m old enough to remember when The Pet Shop Boys released ‘Go West’. I’ve actually been doing a lot of that lately, and it’s led me to discover this gorgeous venue on Watton Street. 
Wolf of Watton has a wonderful story behind it, which tugged at my heartstrings. 
Step-Brothers James Pearce & Nathan Salvalaggio launched Wolf on Watton in September last year, as their first business together.  What’s wonderful is, that it’s housed in the same building their nonna Bianca ran a café called Trovarellis Coffee House way back in the 1970’s. Previous to that, their great-granddad had a fruit shop at this corner spot back in the 1940s. 
It’s a great lineage, and one that’s bound for success, which is exactly what the boys are hoping to achieve with their café by day, a restaurant by evening, and wine bar by night. They became so fed up with having to travel afar for cafes and restaurants, they decided to bring it to their own backyard. Literally, considering the pair live around the corner.  The venue itself boasts an outdoor area, and large open space curated by Studio Equator. It’s surrounded by natures beauty, and sits alongside the Werribee River, which will soon be home to a new development for outdoor entertaining. 
The modern Australia menu offers a range of innovative dishes (see @melbournehuntress for food description and photos). Come for the coffee, stay for the food. It’s not difficult to lose a few hours here. In actual fact, it’s not a loss, it’s the most satisfying win.  I’m convinced it’s the Western Suburbs best-kept secret, and I’m unapologetic in my quest to let the cat out of the bag. Whether you’re north, south, west, or east based; a trip to Werribee for this welcoming canine is a must.

🚨 I need your help, folks 🚨

Which cafes offer coffee brewed via the Chemex?

I love my filter coffee. Not just for it's delicious complex flavours, but it's a far less bitter experience than people imagine coffee to be. 
It also has ample health benefits... I'll save the list for a future post, but let's just say.... coffee has a positive impact on #mentalhealth , in more ways than one! 📸  from @coffeetunes via @jestemmatich 
#tesspresso

I love this hot weather, because it means I get to enjoy delicious cold brew. 
This one tasted like honey grilled apricots.

Coffee? Ethiopian Jigesa. Washed #guji .

🚨 GIVEAWAY TIME 🚨

This year I'll be SHOWING my gratitude with you all by way of vouchers to cafes that I proudly place my logo on. 
It's not only to thank YOU beautiful humans who have shared the journey with me over the past decade, but to allow you the opportunity to experience what I love so much about Melbourne's Coffee Culture.... Head to @melbournehuntress to enter this month's comp. 
Where will you be coffee-ing?

MR ROBERTSON. 
Brought to us by the power duo Christina Panettieri & Dennis Chronis, who also have Mister + Miss in Mont Albert, 
Mr Robertson is located on the former Daniel & Robertson brickworks site in Melbourne's eastern suburb of Nunawading. 
It offers a carefully curated space by the talented @maria.danos ; where Melbourne foodies can indulge in their favourite brunch options (yes they've smashed the avo), coffee geeks can savour their beloved specialty coffee options (care of @axilcoffeeroasters ), and locals can escape the mad rush brought about by the modern era. 
Open 7 days a week; say hi to Adrian if he's on the tools slinging shots.

When you have Mondayitis on a Tuesday.... Time to call in the big guns. .

What's in my cup?  Panama Lotus from @ninetypluscoffee. Roasted by @reformatorycoffeelab, brewed by the master himself @ken_taing. Devoured by your truly. 
I lost myself in this naturally processed Gesha. Think juicy lavish fruits..... And some 🥝🍓🍉🍇🍫

My first meeting with Lee Eman was when he was head barista at The Merchant's Guild in Bentleigh. Since then I’ve watched him pave the way for future baristas, opening his own venue Hendriks in Mordialloc, which he designed and build with his father in law. 
Lee now brings us a fresh new space in the bayside suburb of Beaumaris, which has an interior that’s reflective of the beach vibe that’s merely a 15 minute walk from the Balcombe Road venue. 
Why Gatekeeper? Well, Lee’s original venue location was beside a train station, and so the gatekeeper was a nod to the historic train officer who would manually raise and lower the boom gates. The location fell through, but the name endured. 
I see this Gatekeeper as the commander in charge of controlling access to some delicious brews by way of a brand new Synesso S300 that’s been customised by the world-renowned Specht Designs. 
The menu pays homage to native Australian ingredients, such as lemon myrtle seed bark, wattle seeds, and warrigal greens. 
Head chef Tayne Akyalcin created a delicious Bircher with chia, buckwheat, steel-cut oats, and coconut yoghurt topped with wattle seed, and macadamia crumble, and poached cranberry berries. The Benedict with Smokey mustard served on a Hashbrown is already proving to be a crowd-pleaser. 
Find The Gatekeeper at 336 Balcombe Road.

I'm with my friends @the_real_dads_of_melbourne. 🙏

Who's with us?

I truly believe the time is ripe. You wouldn't over-extract your espresso by choice, so why delay or detract from what we know is the right thing to do? 📣 Scotty From Marketing, it's time to #changethedate, and acknowledge the traditional owners of this beautiful land, what January 26th REALLY means to them. #respect 
Beautiful art thanks to the gorgeous @meganmckean .

Many of you may remember Lilydale’s infamous Mr Ristretto. 
The signature moustache & the bright yellow fit out could be seen from a mile away. Original owner Corey Williams left the site last year, and has returned to this Albert Hill Road location to bring us hos own version of a Brew Lab. 
You’ll still find those crazy freak shakes that the kids love, and I would easily get diabetes just looking at them, along with some delicious coffee offerings. I’m talking natural Colombian Gesha’s, Red honey processed EL Salvadorians, and an anaerobic processed Colombian that rocked the socks off Corey himself. He’s slinging shots by way of a mirror finished Slayer Steam, and brewing some mean beans from a collection of Melbourne roasters. 
Just dont ask him to draw you a pretty picture in your latte .... You'll end up with something the kids won't be able to look at.

Whats new in South Yarra? 
This stylish corner spot! It caught my eye while I was driving along Toorak Road. 
A quick visit soon revealed it to be a 120 seater café, which is the creation of three mates wanting to bring their take on Melbourne coffee culture to the latte loving folks of this inner suburb. Norman, which is named after the cow in City Slickers, is brought to us by Chef Matt Boylan, Andrew Simmonds, and Paul Lange. Matt and Andrew met several years ago when Andrew had the Public Bar in Richmond, and head barista Nick later came into their radar while working at Fourth Chapter in Prahran. I was in awe of Nick’s latte art the moment I saw him pour. Definitely keep an eye out for this guy on the latte art comp scene.

What’s new in South Melbourne?

Well, at the end of 2019, the hospitality gurus from Sixty-One group took over a former stable on a quaint corner of Dorcas Street, and turned it into a foodie sanctuary.

As the idiom implies, they’ve gone the whole nine yards, bringing in designers from Golden by Design to create a fresh space that’s pays homage to Australian flora, and the terracotta and eucalyptus green tones common to this great land.

The menu also features native ingredients that are dished up in the most innovative ways. There’s Wattle seed & thyme damper with bush honey; and the milo mascarpone served on the Aussie (French) Toast took me back to my childhood. They are also offering Califia Oat Milk, which is convenient considering my partner lives in South Melbourne, and only drinks coffee with Oat milk.

Seating around 130, Nine Yards opens 7 days a week, and is located at 228-230 Dorcas Street, South Melbourne.
